<br>
<br>
If you cannot help your child differentiate between games and reality, get neutered and put them up for adoption.  You aren't smart enough to care for yourself, much less raise a child.<br>
<br>
Now what I found interesting was a piece done by an FBI marksman instructor a few years back.  He claimed that the time necessary to teach someone to accurately shoot a pistol was cut dramatically as a direct result of the conditioning and mental reflexes built up by shooter games.  As proof, he invited one of the gaming editors in and had him shooting qualifying rounds with a .45 in under two hours.  He contends that while games don't teach violent behavior, they do train more accurate shooters.  Thus the rise in teh number of deaths per incident we have seen. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=shintenshikurayami>Shintenshi Kurayami</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/29/03 7:29 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> I may have slept through, but...</span><hr size=1> Alright, from what I remember from my freshmen year in a psychology class, it may have been proven that games and other stimuli do not 'make violent people' or 'bring it to surface'...<br>
<br>
Now, let me make sure I have some idea here...<br>
<br>
I think it was somthing like agressive tendancies or behaviors are already ingrained in our DNA. Violent/bloody/shooter games do not 'give us the idea' so to speak, it just makes us think about it more. <br>
<br>
Eq_addict_02 has had a rough day at the office. Wanting to vent his frustrations, he remembers gettin whacked' by that PvP Guild...<br>
<br>
...and remembers when he finally got a few more levels and a chance to CC the bastards. <br>
<br>
He then imagens tossing some high octane mana at his General Supervisor.<br>
<br>
Now, he is not more likely to resort to violence to solve his problems in reality, however, he is more likely to think in terms of present popular stimuli.<br>
<br>
If he was a BasketBall player, he'd think about jamming a Wilson Official GameSize down the CEO's throat. <br>
<br>
Wether or not the people actually do the act of violence is up to their hard coding. <br>
<br>
Video games just give them different idea's on how to do it...either way, they'll do somthing. Even if they have to dry hump somthing to death.<br>
<br>
Guess I sorta contradicted myself, but its been awhile...<br>
<br>
